post_text:
Greetings AWBLA "Eagle Nation" Parents,

Together We Win!!! It is our hope that everyone is healthy and staying masked up. As we approach the end of the 1st marking period, we are diligently preparing for the 2nd Six Weeks. We need to hear from you regarding your scholar(s) learning environment to make the proper preparations. A survey link was emailed yesterday which will inform us of your wishes for your scholar(s) to return either Face-to-Face or continue with our Asynchronous learning AWBLA@HOME. If you did not receive the link or have additional questions, please email info@awbrown.org.

Thank you for your immediate attention to this request and your continuous support.

post_text:
Dear AWLA parents,

Please take a few moments to complete a brief Parent survey that was sent to each primary parent email on Monday. We recommend your feedback to identify your concerns and determine how we can best support you and your scholar(s) for the upcoming fall semester. We are committed to the health and safety of all who enter our campus and your responses will help us plan accordingly.

For any and all Parent Survey issues, please email support@awbrown.org. We are working to resolve all concerns.

Thank you in advance.

post_text:
Heartwarming surprise for 5th Grade Scholar! Master At Arms (MA) Mesha Rabb, who serves as a law enforcement officer in the United States Navy, made it home just in time to surprise her daughter at our Quest Campus today. The scholar was completely unaware that her mother had returned from a yearlong deployment in Djibouti, Africa.

Before the ultimate surprise, mom made arrangements with the Quest front office staff and Parent Liaison to plan her grand entrance. Our sweet 5th-grade scholar was eating lunch during this time. Our Parent Liaison asks the scholar to stand to take a quick photo. While posing, the mother snuck behind her and kissed her on the cheek. The scholar recognized the kiss was from her mother. She turned around and jumped into her mother‚Äôs arms for a heartwarming hug. Her reaction was priceless as the family reunited and her classmates cheered.

Please enjoy pictures of the moment‚Ä¶And, yes, we were all teary-eyed! Thank you, MA Rabb, for your service and sacrifice.
text:
Heartwarming surprise for 5th Grade Scholar! Master At Arms (MA) Mesha Rabb, who serves as a law enforcement officer in the United States Navy, made it home just in time to surprise her daughter at our Quest Campus today. The scholar was completely unaware that her mother had returned from a yearlong deployment in Djibouti, Africa.

Before the ultimate surprise, mom made arrangements with the Quest front office staff and Parent Liaison to plan her grand entrance. Our sweet 5th-grade scholar was eating lunch during this time. Our Parent Liaison asks the scholar to stand to take a quick photo. While posing, the mother snuck behind her and kissed her on the cheek. The scholar recognized the kiss was from her mother. She turned around and jumped into her mother‚Äôs arms for a heartwarming hug. Her reaction was priceless as the family reunited and her classmates cheered.

Please enjoy pictures of the moment‚Ä¶And, yes, we were all teary-eyed! Thank you, MA Rabb, for your service and sacrifice.

Attention Parents/Guardians:
AWBLA is registered to support The Leukemia & Lymphoma Society‚Äôs (LLS) Student Series‚Äô Pennies for Patients. We are joining over 29,000 schools across the nation to make a difference and raise as much money as we can! As our mission states, personal responsibility and responsibilities toward the wider community are taught through unselfish public service and dedication to honoring one's commitments. We are committed to helping find cures for blood cancer patients by "bringing the change" while learning about service, leadership, and philanthropy. Be the change, keep the change, and bring the change. More information will be sent home after Spring Break.

post_text:
AWBLA Leader Profile...Meet the wonderful Kindergarten Teacher of our Quest Campus, Mrs. Shanquia Hardin-Crosby.

This incredible leader shares her "Why" below:

I teach because, for me, it's the most effective and most enjoyable way to change the world. That's the bottom line - I can help change the lives of many scholars, and this is the way I'm choosing to do it. Teaching allows me to work on hearts and minds, to guide scholars in becoming empowered, literate, engaged, creative, liberated human beings who want to change the world. The change I want to see must first begin with me. So this is why I do what I was called to do.

post_text:
AWBLA Leader Profile...Meet the awesome Kindergarten Teacher of our Quest Campus, Ms. Arguadia Cashal Taylor.

This incredible leader shares her "Why" below:

GOD calls children a blessing and a gift. Their spirits are filled with innocence, joy, and laughter.
While attending THE Grambling State University studying Social Work, one of my professors stated that I will be a teacher teaching younger children. GOD ordered my footsteps allowing me to work over 17 years in the Social Work field with children and their families. During that time,
I was able to better understand that you never know what a child has gone through the night before coming to school.
I have taught Kindergarten for 5 years and I am able to greet each one of my scholars with a hug and an "I LOVE YOU!"
My "WHY"! is to love each of my scholars unconditionally and to build trusting relationships with them and their families that will last their lifetime.

AWBLA Leader Profile...Meet the wonderful 4th-grade writing Teacher of our Quest Campus, Mrs. Bridgit Loftis-Jenkins.

This incredible leader shares her "Why" below:

My ‚ÄòWhy‚Äù for being a part of the A.W. Brown Leadership Academy is to make a positive impact on my scholars. My role is to teach my scholars through the example to be kind, respectful, humble, patient, and determined. Teaching is a commitment I take very seriously. I set high, but clear and appropriate expectations for all of my students. As their teacher, I will assist them in using their knowledge and abilities to meet those expectations. I believe my enthusiasm and dedication I have for my profession sets a high standard for my scholars.

AWBLA Leader Profile...Meet the amazing PK3 SOAR Teacher, Ms. Tonisha Hodge.

This incredible leader shares her "Why" below:

I've been working with young children since I was 18 years old, and have been a part of the A.W. Brown family going on 5 years now because teaching is truly my passion. SO when asked "WHY" I do it, the answer is simply to let every child I come in contact with know that they are loved and important, also to encourage each child to be their best selves, and mold them into the leaders I know they are. It warms my heart to see their young faces light up. #heartwork

AWBLA Leader Profile...Meet the awesome Restorative Discipline Coordinator, Dr. Dwain Thompson.

This remarkable leader shares his "Why" below:

My why started when I was born. I was born into a family of pastors, teachers, nurses and people who served the community. The community I grew up in was infested with drugs, violence, and 80% of the black male population ended up in jail. I saw my parents making a difference in the community so I always wanted to follow in their footsteps of impacting the lives of people every day. My goal and why in education are to empower students to be transformational leaders and to understand the power of helping others.

‚ÄúThe best way to find yourself is to lose yourself in the service of others.‚Äù Mahatma Gandhi

AWBLA Leader Profile...Meet the wonderful 5th-grade ELAR/SS Teacher of our Genesis Campus, Mr. Marshall Myers.

This remarkable leader shares his "Why" below:

I had the opportunity to tutor 2nd through 5th-grade students. During that year, I quickly realized that the same problems I had faced as a child were hindering some of the current scholars from performing at their greatest capacities. It was during that time that I realized that my sole purpose in life was to inspire and empower people to become the best version of themselves. Empowering people with the tools needed to become well-rounded individuals and life-long learners is my ‚Äúwhy.‚Äù We were born with the ability to change lives: I refuse to waste an opportunity to do so.

This remarkable leader shares her "Why" below:

I recognized long ago I had an opportunity to directly impact the lives of the children of our future. I have always assisted others while I was in school. Then when I came back to Dallas 14 years ago I was introduced to AWBLA, I knew this would be where I could make the biggest impact on children that I personally can relate to. I have grown up in so many aspects of my life here at AWBLA. I have witnessed our successes, our failures, our accomplishments, and our shortcomings but through it all, I stayed focused. Why? Because I know all the little Janes and Joes are waiting on me! The daily smiles, hugs, light bulb moments, gratitude shown, peep talks, lessons, collaborations, trainings, past students who come back just to let you know they are alright, meetings, bonds formed, counseling sessions, and mentorships as I rush in the mornings to be on time makes it all worthwhile.

post_text:
AWBLA Leader Profile...Meet the awesome Director of Information Technology, Mr. Erin Holmes.

This incredible leader shares his "Why" below:

I have worked in the education field for over 10 years in many capacities from a custodian, teacher assistant, teacher of record, and now as the Director of Technology. These different views have provided me with a unique perspective and helped me to understand my purpose not only professionally, but personally as well. I have attained an Associate of Arts degree from the University of Phoneix and scheduled to graduate with my Bachelor's in Computer Science Spring of '19.

My mission (why) is to provide tangible learning experiences through the use of technology that will assist our scholars to become media literate as well as build proficiency in a technology-driven society.

As a child growing up in the church that birthed A.W. Brown Leadership Academies, I am fortunate enough to have a unique perspective on the founding vision of the school and I am overly excited I get the chance to help make that vision come to life!

AWBLA Leader Profile...Meet the fantastic PreK Coach, Mrs. Jill Walker.

This incredible leader shares her "Why" below:

My ‚ÄúWhy‚Äù comes full circle. I started my teaching career at A. W. Brown in 2002 educating third-grade scholars. I left in 2007, had various educational experiences then returned back home to A. W. Brown in 2014. I use that word ‚Äúhome‚Äù with sincerity and humility. Throughout my career in education, I realized I was called back to serve in a capacity different from the one in which I started. I love all things PreK and being able to grow our scholars from the ground up and inspiring parents to extend the learning at home has been an amazing adventure. Even more so, being able to work in leadership with colleagues I have known since 2002 further solidifies my purpose in life: to share my love of learning to empower children and adults to become productive citizens in society.

post_text:
AWBLA Leader Profile...Meet the fantastic Assistant Principal of our Genesis Elementary Campus, Mr. Anthony Jefferson.

This incredible leader shares his "Why" below:

One of the greatest moments of my existence was the day that I completed my first year of teaching. It was then realized that I possessed the power to affect change in the lives of others. The stride in the walk, the smile on a face, the hope in the eyes of a scholar who has accomplished a task well ignited the flame in my spirit for heart work. The realization that in order to become that flame of hope for others became evident. This insight that it requires hard work began to settle in my consciousness. To that avail, I knew that I was called to be an educator.

AWBLA Leader Profile...Meet the sensational principal of our SOAR (PK) program, Dr Kim Dalcour.

This marvelous leader shares her "Why" below:

My why is two-fold. In my current role as the pre-kindergarten principal, my charge is to grow teachers to impact scholars, making sure I create an environment where every teacher feels safe and free to teach...guiding teachers to perfect their craft and move to greater heights. The second and most important part of my why is growing teachers to water our S.E.E.D.S, ensuring our students are Smart, Effect, Efficient, Discipline Scholars that will positively impact our community. When the S.E.E.D.S. are watered by our teachers, the school, community, and world will be impacted.

AWBLA Leader Profile...Meet the extraordinary principal of Quest Middle School, Mrs Shenikwa Cager.

This phenomenal leader shares her "Why" below:

My 5th-grade teacher, Mrs Black, impacted my life in an indescribable way and I knew then I would be an educator.
I stand on the broad shoulders of people who believed in me, starting with my parents. I, too, believe all children deserve to touch success. I do what I do because my daughters are watching me. I do what I do because my supportive husband allows me to do it. I do what I do because I‚Äôm an African American girl from Oak Cliff with a passion to reach, teach and lead others to BeBetter.DoDifferent.GoHigher!

Each day I hope that I leave others the way Mrs Black left me...BETTER!

post_text:
Littlest scholars SOAR with A.W. Brown
Beginning June 4, 2018

Do you have or know of a family with PK-3 or PK-4 year old aged children? If so, AW BROWN is transforming the landscape of early childhood education in the State of Texas. Because we believe an early start is the best start, all of our PK programs will be full day, year round!!!

If you are already enrolled in our PK-3 or PK-4 program for the 2018-19 year you will receive information regarding a June 4th start of school.

There are only 50 additional full day PK-3 slots and 50 additional full day PK-4 slots available. Age is always calculated as of September 1 of the current school year (for the purposes of establishing eligibility).

Log on to awbrown.org and signup by pressing the New Scholar Registration button. Note: Eligibility requirements for PK and AWB attendance zones are in effect.

Start Date: June 4, 2018
Pre-Kindergarten Classes: Full Day
Hours: Monday ‚Äì Friday; 8am-3pm
Before and After School Care Available

#SOARWITHAWB
#THEBESTISYETTOCOME

post_text: The Golden Eagles' Track Team was "on track" at the STATE MEET of the TEXAS CHARTER SCHOOL ACADEMIC & ATHLETIC LEAGUE in Georgetown, Texas. The A. W. Brown Boys and Girls Track Team finished first and second in every event that they participated in. On the girls side: bringing home the GOLD in the open 400m run is STATE CHAMPION Candis Clements, and bringing home the SILVER in the open 400m run is STATE RUNNER UP A‚Äômarie Roman. The girls 4x400m relay consisting of Candis Clements, A‚Äômarie Roman, Makayla Copeland, and Sania Abercrombie also brought home the GOLD and are STATE CHAMPIONS. On the boys side: bringing home the GOLD in the open 400m run is STATE CHAMPION Treyshawn Williams, while Jabrehon Peters claimed STATE RUNNER UP in the shot put, bringing home the SILVER medal. The boys 4x100m relay consisting of Adrain Nobles, Treyshawn Williams, Terrence Allen, and Aaron Nobles brought home the GOLD and are STATE CHAMPIONS. These EAGLES can really fly!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!! Congratulations!!! We Love You! Shout out to Coach Reed and his coaching staff.

post_text:
As we prepare to return tomorrow, I wanted to provide some resources that you can discuss and share with your scholars and also utilize in order to mitigate the incidence of flu or flu-like illnesses in our District.

The most important considerations in fighting the spread of the flu virus are:

1) Staying home when ill (scholars AND staff with temperatures > 100 degrees must be fever-free without the use of fever-reducing medication for 24 hrs prior to returning to work/school).
2) Scholars and staff with uncontrolled cough require further evaluation.
3) Proper hand-washing techniques help decrease the spread of germs and illness.
4) Covering coughs and sneezes.
5) Get immunized for the flu, if that is your preference. Recommend the flu immunization for your scholars, if that is the preference of their parents.
6) Ensure that you are getting adequate rest and eating the proper nutrients.

Please take the time to discuss proper hand-washing and covering coughs and sneezing with your scholars.

Respectfully,

Sherry-Ann Agbabiaka, RN
Health Services Coordinator
